snippet.textDisplay: This system has to be a tactic to distract other teams and probably has no gains to Mercedes at all. If it were giving them an advantage, they would have hidden it away much better than something as obvious as pulling on the steering wheel. It would have been simple to keep the wheel static but have the column telescopic so it could be moved with a foot pedal making it much harder for the competition to spot. Far more likely they tested it and found it gave them no advantage but put it on to divert attention from something else that does give an advantage and let the competition waste their time and resources on copying the DAS before they discover there were far more productive areas they could have developed.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is one more element that is not being talked about with this DAS device. The point of toe adjustment in the front is to help with front end balance for corners and braking. More toe out allows the inside tire to follow a smaller radius (aka turns more) than the outside tire (aka turns less). Too much toe-out can make a car twitchy under braking, but too much toe-in makes the car push in the corners (not to mention drags the inside tire across the tarmac creating extra wear and extra temp). If used properly by the Merc drivers, this will most likely improve (lower) tire degradation on long race runs without impacting lap times too much for a team that are already strong in that department!

As far as legality goes. There are some conflicting regs in the 2020 rules which makes this a gray area imo. Either way, the FIA needs to clear the legality of this now so this talk won't go on all season like the last two years with Ferrari in their battery and fuel flow.

snippet.textDisplay:
is not a regular:
technical regulation 2020 which in two points seems to contradict the Federation. Article 3.8, for example, has as its object the aerodynamic influence and establishes that "with the exception of the parts necessary for the correction referred to in article 3.6.8, any system of the car that uses the movement of the driver as a means of altering the aerodynamic characteristics of the car is prohibited ". And in the case of DAS there is a movement. Article 10.2, on the subject of suspension geometry, in point 10.2.3 explains that "no adjustments can be made to any suspension system while the machine is in motion".

I wonder if this was an idea from the Brawn era that has finally found the ability to be implemented?
Back in the Brawn days there were plenty of innovative ideas floating about.  The double-diffuser became legendary, but I do wonder how many ideas were a bit too way-out, difficult to implement or just too much trouble that like this may have now surfaced as the gaps between teams become closer.
